GROUP: Source: WHO Immunization Data portal [WHO/UNICEF electronic Joint Reporting Form on Immunization (eJRF); WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC): 2024 revision (completed 15 July 2025), data from 1980-2024; WHO Estimates of Human papillomavirus immunization coverage (HPV Estimates): 2024 revision (completed 15 July 2025), data from 2010-2024; Protection at Birth for Tetanus (PAB) estimates: 2024 revision]

Update: Administrative and official reported coverage data are collected annually through the WHO/UNICEF Joint Reporting Form on Immunization (JRF) exercise (occurring in the Q1-Q2 of each year). Country data (including historical data) are updated and made available as received. WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC) national, regional, and global data are updated annually and released in mid-July.

Data use: Immunization Agenda 2030 (IA2030), Strategic Advisory Group of Experts on Immunization (SAGE), WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC) / WHO Estimates of Human papillomavirus (HPV) immunization coverage, WHO recommendations, risk assessments, publications, guidance, and strategies.

Comments: The quality of the estimates are determined by the quality and availability of empirical data. Vaccination is relatively easy to measure and two methods - facility reports (or administrative data) and surveys - have been developed, each of which, when properly designed and implemented, provides accurate and reliable direct measures of coverage levels. Implemented jointly, they provide a validation of coverage levels. However, both methods are subject to biases. In some instances, these biases may be identified and corrected and we have attempted to do so. These data are supplemented with local consultations that often explain inconsistencies and anomalies in the data and provide insight into forces that influence coverage levels. More importantly, WHO and UNICEF are working closely with countries to improve the quality and usefulness of coverage monitoring data systems.

These estimates should be used alongside the accompanying text that provides additional information regarding each estimate. Please refer to each specific coverage reference tab on the WHO Immunization Data portal to view data limitations, glossary, and metadata.

CODE: number of doses administered and administrative coverage"

GROUP: Data not always the same as the country official estimates and WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC).
Data updated within 24 hours of official country reporting through the WHO/UNICEF electronic Joint Reporting Form on Immunization (eJRF) Routine coverage topic.
HepBBD refers to birth dose, however, occasionally countries report a later HepB 1st dose.
HepB3 dose refers to 3rd dose administered to infants and not to adolescents
WHO displays data as reported by national authorities.
These data are based on administrative system as reported annually in the WHO/UNICEF electronic Joint Reporting Form (eJRF).

Administrative measure: Countries are instructed to report routine immunization coverage using the administrative method, that is, using data on the number of doses administered divided by an estimated target population, usually surviving infants or live birth for doses recommended in the first year of life. Only doses given that are part of the national immunization schedule are to be included.
Preferred data source: National immunization programme information system, Household surveys, other administrative systems
For more information on the JRF go to: https://www.who.int/teams/immunization-vaccines-and-biologicals/immunization-analysis-and-insights/global-monitoring/who-unicef-joint-reporting-process.
List of antigens collected at the global level in the WHO/UNICEF electronic Joint Reporting form (eJRF) 2024 for which administrative coverage data is available (data collected in 2025):

Instructions: Report routine immunization coverage in this table using the administrative method, that is, using data on the number of doses administered. 
 
Include only doses given that are part of the national immunization schedule. Usually this means that these doses are recorded on the recipient's immunization personal record. 
 
Routine immunization may include additional immunization delivery strategies (such as Periodic Intensification of Routine Immunization) or school-based immunization. 
 
Not considered "routine" are doses that are given as part of "supplemental immunization activities" (SIAs), i.e. doses that are given outside the immunization schedule such as, campaigns where persons receive vaccines regardless of their previous vaccination status. SIAs are usually intended to achieve accelerated disease control goals. SIAs, as well as vitamin A distribution, should be reported in the Supplementary activities topic in the eJRF.

-HepB, birth dose (given within 24 hours of birth)
[Instructions: Provide ONLY hepatitis B vaccine doses given within 24 hours of birth. If time of birth is unknown, please provide doses of hepatitis B vaccine given within first day of life (i.e. if the infant is born on day 0, include all HepB doses given on days 0 and 1). This indicator is NOT equivalent to HepB1.]

-HepB, birth dose total (including those given within and after 24 hours of birth) 
[Instructions: Provide ALL hepatitis B vaccine doses given at any time from birth up until hepatitis B first dose (HepB1) is due, or as per country guidance on upper age range. This indicator is NOT equivalent to HepB1. Please specify the country policy on upper age limit for hepatitis B birth dose.]
-Inactivated polio-containing vaccine, 2nd dose (applicable only to all countries in the WHO Region of the Americas and OPV-using countries)

-Fractional inactivated polio-containing vaccine, 1st dose
[Instructions: If IPV is administered in fractional doses, please provide data for both first and second fractional doses.]

-Fractional inactivated polio-containing vaccine, 2nd dose
[Instructions: If IPV is administered in fractional doses, please provide data for both first and second fractional doses.]
-Fractional inactivated polio-containing vaccine, 3rd dose (applicable only to countries administering 3 doses of IPV fractional dose)

-Polio, 3rd dose 
[Instructions: This refers to the third dose of polio vaccine, excluding polio 0 (zero), if such a dose is included in the national schedule.
Indicate OPV3 based on the below primary series for Polio immunization:
1. OPV + IPV (OPV / OPV / OPV+IPV): schedule recommended by the Strategic Advisory Group of Experts (SAGE) in 2012 to all OPV only using countries.
 • OPV3 corresponds to the third dose of bOPV, not taking into account OPV birth dose (if given)
2. OPV + fIPV (OPV+fIPV / OPV / OPV+fIPV): modified schedule from the original recommendation to allow for the use of fIPV
 • OPV3 corresponds to the third dose of bOPV, not taking into account OPV birth dose (if given)
3. Sequential IPV (IPV / IPV / OPV): in sequential schedules both IPV and OPV are given, but not at the same/visit. PAHO only. 
 • OPV3 corresponds to the third dose of polio containing vaccine, in this case the dose bOPV
4. Sequential fIPV (fIPV / fIPV / OPV): same as above but administering fractional dose. PAHO only.
 • OPV3 corresponds to the third dose of polio containing vaccine, in this case bOPV
 5. IPV only (IPV / IPV /IPV): Only IPV containing vaccine given (either in combination or standalone)
 OPV3 corresponds to the third dose of the IPV containing vaccine used in the country (i.e. Penta IPV, Hexavalent or standalone)]

-HepB, 3rd dose
[Instructions: In countries using monovalent vaccine for all doses, this refers to the third dose of hepatitis B vaccine, including the birth dose, if such a dose is included in the national schedule.
In countries that are using monovalent vaccine for the birth dose and combination vaccine for the subsequent doses, HepB3 will refer to the third dose of the combination vaccine in addition to the birth dose.]

-Measles-containing vaccine, 1st dose
[Instructions: Measles-containing vaccine (MCV) includes measles vaccine, measles-rubella vaccine, measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, etc. Fill in the rows for both MCVs and RCVs even if they were given in combination.]

-Rubella-containing vaccine, 1st dose
[Instructions: Rubella-containing vaccine (RCV) includes rubella vaccine, measles-rubella vaccine, measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, etc. Fill in the rows for both MCVs and RCVs even if they were given in combination.]

-Measles-containing vaccine, 2nd dose
[Instructions: Measles-containing vaccine (MCV) includes measles vaccine, measles-rubella vaccine, measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, etc. Fill in the rows for both MCVs and RCVs even if they were given in combination.]

-Meningococcal A conjugate vaccine, last dose (Countries outside of the meningitis belt only)
[Instructions: The coverage data is only requested for Meningococcal A conjugate monovalent vaccine (MenAfriVac), not for other Meningococcal A-containing conjugate vaccines. Please report the coverage of the last dose of the schedule used for Meningococcal A conjugate monovalent vaccine of the primary series.]

-Meningococcal ACYW conjugate vaccine, last dose (Countries outside of the meningitis belt only) [Instructions: Please report the coverage of the last dose of the schedule used for Meningococcal ACYW conjugate vaccine of the primary series.]
-Meningococcal B vaccine, last dose [Instructions: Please report the coverage of the last dose of the schedule used for Meningococcal B vaccine of the primary series.]

-Tetanus toxoid-containing vaccine, 2nd and subsequent doses
[Instructions: The number of live births can be used as a proxy for the total number of pregnant women.]

-Protection at birth (PAB) against neonatal tetanus
[Instructions: This refers to children who are protected at birth (PAB) against neonatal tetanus by their mother's TT status; this information is collected during the DTP1 visit - a child is deemed protected if the mother has received 2 doses of TT in the last pregnancy or at-least 3 doses of TT in previous years. 
If the country does not calculate PAB, please select "NR" for not relevant.]

-HPV Female, 1st dose
[Instructions: Report target and doses administered and coverage with the first dose of HPV. 
Report for females and males in the separate rows. If disaggregated data is not available, please report same numbers in male and female rows.]

-HPV Female, final dose
[Instructions: When multi-dose (2-doses or 3-doses) HPV schedules are used in the national schedule, report target and doses administered and coverage for the final dose (the second or third dose for 2- or 3-dose schedules respectively). If reporting on single dose schedule, leave blank and report in "HPV Female, 1st dose" row. 
Report for females and males in the separate rows. If disaggregated data is not available, please report same numbers in male and female rows.]

-HPV Male, 1st dose
[Instructions: Report target and doses administered and coverage with the first dose of HPV. 
Report for females and males in the separate rows. If disaggregated data is not available, please report same numbers in male and female rows.]

-HPV Male, final dose
[Instructions: When multi-dose (2-doses or 3-doses) HPV schedules are used in the national schedule, report target and doses administered and coverage for the final dose (the second or third dose for 2- or 3-dose schedules respectively). If reporting on single dose schedule, leave blank and report in "HPV Male, 1st dose" row. 
Report for females and males in the separate rows. If disaggregated data is not available, please report same numbers in male and female rows.]

-Malaria vaccine, 1st dose (applicable only to all countries in the WHO African Region, WHO Eastern Mediterranean Region, WHO South-East Asia Region)
[Instructions: It is appropriate to use the same target population as that used for other vaccines recommended for infants and children of similar age. In case the vaccine is introduced in some parts of the country only, please use the annual target population in areas where the vaccine is used. Please use the annual target population in the denominator, irrespective of the month of vaccine introduction.]

-Malaria vaccine, 3rd dose (applicable only to all countries in the WHO African Region, WHO Eastern Mediterranean Region, WHO South-East Asia Region)
[Instructions: It is appropriate to use the same target population as that used for other vaccines recommended for infants and children of similar age. In case the vaccine is introduced in some parts of the country only, please use the annual target population in areas where the vaccine is used. Please use the annual target population in the denominator, irrespective of the month of vaccine introduction.]

-Malaria vaccine, 4th dose (applicable only to all countries in the WHO African Region, WHO Eastern Mediterranean Region, WHO South-East Asia Region)
[Instructions: It is appropriate to use the same target population as that used for other vaccines recommended for infants and children of similar age. In case the vaccine is introduced in some parts of the country only, please use the annual target population in areas where the vaccine is used. Please use the annual target population in the denominator, irrespective of the month of vaccine introduction.]
-Influenza residents living in long term care facilities
Note: Additional antigens are collected from selected number of countries in various regions that may/may not be included in the dataset.

WHO displays data as reported by national authorities.
These data are based on official and administrative system as reported annually in the WHO/UNICEF electronic Joint Reporting Form (eJRF) Routine coverage and Official estimates topics.

Official estimates may be based on data from the administrative method, from surveys, or from other sources. Immunization coverage figures from administrative system can be biased or inaccurate. Hence, national authorities have the opportunity to provide estimates of what the most likely true coverage is. This will help to interpret the administrative data.
Preferred data source: National immunization programme information system, Household surveys, other administrative systems
Preference is given to official figures, but if missing, values are also taken from the administrative figures.
For more information on the JRF go to: https://www.who.int/teams/immunization-vaccines-and-biologicals/immunization-analysis-and-insights/global-monitoring/who-unicef-joint-reporting-process

Instructions: It is important to understand that immunization coverage figures from the Administrative coverage section can be biased or inaccurate. Hence, the Official estimates topic gives national authorities the opportunity to provide estimates of what the most likely true coverage is. These official estimates may be based on data from the administrative method, from surveys, or from other sources. This exercise is extremely important to interpret the data.

Data source: WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC), 2024 Revision (completed 15 July 2025), data from 1980-2024.

These data show the latest WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC). They are based on data reported by 25 June 2025. WUENIC estimates include a Grade of Confidence assigned to each estimated data point. The current release of the WUENIC with data up to 2024 (released in 2025) includes estimates for WHO Member States, including those that did not report 2024 data. For these non-reporting countries, estimates were extrapolated from the last point informed by empirical data. Similarly, global and regional coverages, values were extrapolated from 2023 for non-reporting countries. Non-reporting countries represent ≈4% of the global 2024 cohort. WUENIC data time series are updated annually in mid-July based on available reported data and survey results. Please be sure to reference the 2024 revision (completed 15 July 2025) as the data is used.

The survey information is available from the WHO Immunization Data portal > All data page > Additional datasets > Coverage Survey Data Excel download: https://immunizationdata.who.int/global?topic=Additional-datasets&location=.

These estimates are based on quantitative data: 1) Country reported coverage data (official and administrative coverage) and 2) survey coverage (from survey final reports, and complying with minimum set of quality criteria), and are informed by contextual information (e.g., stock-outs, changes in schedule, and other relevant information where available and appropriate). As such, these estimates are affected by the availability and quality of the underlying empirical data.

The WHO/UNICEF Estimates of National Immunization Coverage (WUENIC) do not represent an endorsement to reported or survey data. Their main focus has been to present a consistent coverage trend analysis.

All reasonable precautions have been taken by the World Health Organization (WHO) and United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) to verify the information contained in this publication. Note: If two states combined into one, data are presented only for the new entity: i.e. Federal German Republic & German Democratic Republic data are now under Germany.
Data from new entities emerging from older entities are reported from their birth date, whereas the original entity data are retained until their cessation.

The following antigens are included in the WUENIC process: 
 -BCG: Bacille Calmette Guérin vaccine (for countries having included it in their universal national immunization schedule at birth)
 -DTPCV1: First dose of diphtheria toxoid, tetanus toxoid and pertussis-containing vaccine
 -DTPCV3: Third dose of diphtheria toxoid, tetanus toxoid and pertussis-containing vaccine
 -HEPB_BD: Hepatitis B birth dose estimates are for doses given within 24 hours after birth (for countries where HepB birth does is universally recommended and data is collected for dose administered within 24 hours of birth)
 -HEPB3: Third dose of hepatitis B vaccine
 -HIB3: Third dose of Haemophilus influenzae type b vaccine
 -IPV1: First dose of inactivated polio vaccine (for countries using OPV vaccine for routine or supplementary activities and countries using IPV only)
- IPV2: Second dose of inactivated polio vaccine (IPV2 coverage estimates produced for OPV using countries)
 -MCV1: First dose of Measles-containing vaccine
 -MCV2: Coverage estimates are for the nationally recommended age for the second dose of measles containing vaccine.
 -MCV2X2: Measles-containing vaccine 2nd dose by 2 years of age
 -MENA_C: One dose of meningococcal A conjugate vaccine (MengA coverage estimates produced for countries in the meningitis belt of sub-Saharan Africa).
 -PCV3: Third dose of pneumococcal conjugate vaccine
 -POL3: Third dose of polio vaccine
 -RCV1: Rubella containing vaccine (1st dose) (for countries with Rubella containing vaccines in routine schedule. Estimate based on MCV vaccine)
 -ROTAC: Rotavirus last dose (2nd or 3rd depending on schedule)
 -YFV: Yellow fever (YF for countries at risk and YF in routine immunization schedule, coverage is estimated for the entire birth cohort of the country)
 
Measles 2nd dose estimates are provided for the age cohort according to the administration recommended in national immunization schedule. Global and regional coverage estimates are made for vaccinations by the nationally recommended age. 
 
Estimates for a dose of inactivated polio vaccine (IPV) begin in 2015 following the Global Polio Eradication Initiative's Polio Eradication and Endgame Strategic Plan: 2013-2018 which recommended at least one full dose or two fractional doses of IPV into routine immunization schedules as a strategy to mitigate the potential consequences should any re-emergence of type 2 poliovirus occur following the planned withdrawal of Sabin type 2 strains from oral polio vaccine (OPV).

Aggregated estimates groupings: Global, WHO Regions, UNICEF Regions, World Bank Classification (set on 1 July 2025 update: https://datahelpdesk.worldbank.org/knowledgebase/articles/906519-world-bank-country-and-lending-groups), Gavi Eligibility (https://www.gavi.org/types-support/sustainability/eligibility), World Economic Situation and Prospects 2025: https://unctad.org/publication/world-economic-situation-and-prospects-2025)

Method of estimation of global and regional aggregates: Global and regional coverage is a weighted sum of WHO/UNICEF estimates of national coverage by target population from the United Nations Population Division's World Population Prospects. The size of the target population is the national annual number of infants surviving their first year of life.
Births from World Population Prospects: United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2024). World Population Prospects 2024, Online Edition.
Surviving Infants from World Population Prospects: United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2024). World Population Prospects 2024, Online Edition.

For more information on estimates methods please consult the web site: https://www.who.int/teams/immunization-vaccines-and-biologicals/immunization-analysis-and-insights/global-monitoring/immunization-coverage/who-unicef-estimates-of-national-immunization-coverage.
﻿WHO estimates of Human papillomavirus immunization coverage

Data source: WHO estimates of Human papillomavirus immunization coverage, 2024 Revision (completed 15 July 2025), data from 2010-2024. These data show the latest HPV Estimates. They are based on data reported until 20 June 2025.

The methodology for HPV vaccine coverage estimates was developed by WHO in 2009. Since 2010 the WHO/UNICEF Joint Reporting Form collects data on HPV vaccine schedule and doses delivered to females by actual age from 9 to 14 and 15+ year old in order to start calculating coverage measures. Starting 2019 also doses delivered to males, as well as official denominators and coverage estimates are included in the Joint Reporting Form. A cumulative, cohort method to track trends and compare between countries through an indicator of coverage by 15 years of age was identified. In 2018, a further consultation on the topic of HPV coverage measurement identified the need for an additional coverage measure to assess the coverage by schedule in a calendar year. Based on the consensus, a second indicator, called programme performance was established that captured the performance of the programme in the previous calendar year. Both indicators take into account the doses delivered to girls who started the first dose between 9 and 14 years of age and are disaggregated for first and completed dose to account for changes over time in the number of doses in the HPV vaccination schedules. To establish denominators, the methodology uses as a default the UN Population Division county estimates. To deal with the different ways countries set and change eligibility criteria over time, a normalization process is used to translate eligibility into denominators. This includes translating school grade eligibility in population cohorts and dealing with multiple cohort eligibility (changes) over time. Global and regional coverage is a weighted sum of WHO/UNICEF HPV Estimates of national coverage by 15 years old girls from the United Nations Population Division's World Population Prospects (United Nations, Department of Economic and Social Affairs, Population Division (2024). World Population Prospects 2024, Online Edition).

﻿Protection At Birth (PAB) against tetanus with Tetanus toxoid-containing vaccines (TTCV) 2024 revision

Definition of PAB: The reported Protection at Birth against tetanus (PAB) coverage by WHO and UNICEF is an estimate for a reference year of the percentage of pregnant women protected by tetanus toxoid containing vaccines (TTCV) who would give birth to a child protected against tetanus as a result of maternal transfer of antibodies through the placenta.

A pregnant woman is considered protected against tetanus if she is still in the period of protection that follows the last dose of TTCV she received during her previous pregnancies or outside of pregnancies (i.e. any TTCV administered in infancy - DTP or Pentavalent), second year of life, school health services, periodic SIAs/ campaigns in high risk areas, post injury, etc.)

PAB is influenced by the TTCV schedule followed based on the WHO recommendation as the duration of protection is dependent on the number of properly-spaced doses of TTCV received. Six doses of TTCV are recommended if started in infancy while 5 doses are recommended if started in the reproductive age. In terms of protection from tetanus for women starting in the reproductive age:
-TT protection starts about 15 days after the second dose of TTCV and last for approximately 3 years,
-the 3rd dose of TTCV is administered at least 6 months after the second dose and extends the protection to about 5 years,
-the 4th dose should be administered at least one year after the 3rd dose and protects for at least 10 years
-the 5th dose administered at least 1 year after the 4th dose and protects throughout the reproductive age, and probably for life.

Consequently, monitoring the level of PAB is a complex process given the various opportunities for a woman to receive doses of TTCV vaccine and the absence of permanent record for all doses ever administered makes it even more complex.
2) The source of information to estimate PAB and their respective accuracy challenges.

-Administrative reporting: Countries routinely submit yearly report on TT2+ coverage data through the health management information system (HIMS). TT2+ represents the number of protective doses of TTCV (TT2 + TT3 + TT4 + TT5) given to pregnant women over the last 12 months divided by the number of pregnant women in the population (annual target). This method tends to underestimate TT protection as evidenced by many coverage and TT sero surveys, and some of the reasons for the underestimation include:
--Incomplete and delayed reporting from health facilities for the previous year and non-incorporation of delayed reports in the HIMS.

--Many pregnant women who have received 5 TTCV doses and do not need further doses are not included in the numerator while protected. This underestimates the level of tetanus protection affecting a growing number of well performing countries.

--The History of previous TTCV doses even during past pregnancies are often not taken into account by health workers at antenatal care (ANC) clinics in absence of documentation and the TTCV vaccination schedule is reinitiated. Reviews of immunization registers in ANC clinics and EPI centres that have been running for over 20 years have shown excessively low number of 3rd, 4th and 5th doses administered.

--Most often the reporting excludes TTCV doses administered outside of pregnancies (campaign doses in high risk areas, MenA vaccine doses (in sub-Saharan African meningitis belt countries as the vaccine uses TT as a carrier protein), school TT doses, post injury dose, early infant TTCV dose such as DTP or pentavalent and TTCV doses administered by the private sector).

--In many countries number of expected pregnant women is often the results of projected data based upon an old census and leads to inaccurate denominators resulting in flaws in reported TT2+ coverage.

-TT coverage surveys: TT protection by at least 2 doses is usually assessed as part of EPI coverage surveys, MICS and DHS, taking into account the history of TTCV doses administered during and outside pregnancies (TT SIAs, school-based doses). Those surveys are usually conducted with 3 to 5 years’ intervals. They usually show a higher level of TT protection than the administrative routine reporting of TT2+ coverage if well planned and executed. However, surveys have suffered from few challenges including:
--Some bias may occur when coverage surveys are carried out or influenced by EPI staff.

--An over reliance on the history of TT doses administered due to poor retention of documented evidence of past TT doses administered during successive pregnancies and outside pregnancies (campaign doses) may seriously underestimate true TT protection (as evidenced in comparative Ethiopia coverage surveys DHS vs EPI).
--Exclusion of valid doses of TTCV administered in infancy and, most recently, exclusion of doses of MenA  administered successfully in sub-Saharan African countries.

--They are dependent on good planning including sampling, quality execution and quality supervision of the survey. The long questionnaires in the DHS survey may lead to respondent’s fatigue and influence the responses.

--DHS and MICS survey protocols vary from one country to another with regard to TT protection assessment method and sometimes only look at pregnant women in last 3 years having received one or two doses of TTCV, ignoring previous TTCV doses administered during and outside pregnancies.
--Results of coverage surveys have systematically shown to be lower than sero surveys results (Burundi[1], CAR[2], Haiti)

-Routine administrative monitoring of Protection At Birth (PAB) methodology assessed at DTP1 immunization contact: This method uses infant immunization registers to routinely assess TT protection based on history of TT doses administered during past pregnancies and outside pregnancies (TT SIAs), and has proved much more accurate than the classic administrative method of TT2+ reporting specially in few well performing countries like Tunisia, Morocco and Syria When it was initiated in the late 1990s. However, it has faced few challenges:

--It has only been adopted nationwide by few well performing countries because it requires a high level of health worker training and supervision during early implementation to ensure quality of the assessment.
--It is dependent on good retention of card(s) or reliable immunization history

--It can only bring PAB coverage up to at least DTP1 levels which is frequently over 80% in many countries except in high risk areas targeted by TT SIAs to eliminate MNT where coverage for DTP1 may be low.
--To be valuable it requires effective nationwide implementation.

While most of the countries that currently routinely monitor PAB do so, during DTP1 immunization contact, all post-natal care visits (currently recommended at 24 hours, day 3, and between 7–14 days and 6 weeks after delivery) present an opportunity to check PAB. With the increased integration of maternal, post-natal and vaccination services there are other contact opportunities where PAB status could be assessed and recorded

-Results of TT protection levels obtained from MNTE validation surveys: The Lot Quality Assurance – Cluster Sampling survey conducted to validate the elimination of MNT is implemented in the least performing district of a country as regards risk indicators for MNT. This validation survey includes an assessment of TT protection through the history of TT doses during and outside of pregnancies and relies on an in-depth training and supervision of interviewers. The results can be used as a useful proxy indicator of the country’s PAB protection performance as the survey is carried out in the least performing district of the country. However,
--The nationwide TT protection level can be even higher than that of the LQA district that often has poorest EPI and routine TT coverage.
--The least performing district has often been targeted by TT SIAs, which may not be a true reflection of nationwide TT protection if TT SIAs have been the main reason for TT coverage achievements.

-Results of TT SIAS (2 or 3 rounds, or one periodic corrective round) targeting women of reproductive age in high risk districts: TT SIAs are conducted in identified high risk districts (reporting less than 80% TT2+ coverage, and less than 70% skilled birth attendance coverage). In few countries a nationwide exercise was conducted (i.e. Angola, Burkina Faso, Chad , Cote d’Ivoire, DRC, Laos, Liberia, Niger, PNG, Sierra Leone,  Timor Leste) and periodic TT SIAs’ corrective rounds are conducted to sustain and provide long lasting TT protection where the health system is still not performing well. The proportion of country population targeted by TT SIAs and TT2 SIAs’ coverage achievements in WRA can be used to adjust overall country PAB performance among pregnant women. However,
--Sometimes the administrative reports of TT SIAs performance may be inaccurate due to the classic denominator issues.
--Some countries report coverage by round of SIAs instead of by doses of TT received.

--Duration of TT Protection following TT SIAs and periodic additional TT SIA doses  is usually a conservative estimate as the SIAs target high risk areas where WRAs may still have up to 70% TT protection from routinely administrated doses for which there are no records. . Therefore the duration of protection following TT SIAs’ doses may be much longer as the number of TTCV doses ever received may be incorrect.

-Results of MenA campaign in Sub-Saharan African countries: MenA vaccination campaigns have been very successful in providing one dose of TT to those 29 years and below including females. It acts as a TT booster dose for WRA targeted by TT SIAs in high risk areas of underperforming countries (Chad, Mali, Niger, etc.) providing a longer TT immunity to those who already received previous doses including in areas unable to establish a strong routine TTCV programme. However, The impact of MenA vaccination may be more important in delivering an additional high coverage 3rd dose in high risk areas as the 3rd dose coverage is often the lowest during TTCV SIAs.

-Results of TT sero surveys: TT sero surveys’ results are the most precise and reliable markers of PAB protection as they include the benefits of any doses of TTCV administered since infancy that no other method can account for. Sero surveys do not rely on history of TTCV doses administered, and account for possible poor quality of TT vaccine. They have systematically revealed higher protection levels than TT coverage surveys and are higher than administratively reported PAB (Burundi1, CAR2, Haiti). Similar higher difference in protection levels have been documented at district level in Uganda and Kenya.
Serology will be the most appropriate tool to monitor TT protection nationwide in the future if incorporated into EPI coverage survey, MICS or DHS.
Unfortunately, very few countries have carried out sero surveys due to high cost, limited technical capacity implications and absence of clearance from the MICS and DHS teams.

-PAB modeling created by WHO in early 2003 to estimate PAB for each country: The model was designed to accommodate the benefits of all doses of TTCV administered during infancy (DTP containing vaccines), during pregnancies and during TT SIAs, and duration of protection following each subsequent dose. However, in many low income and lower middle income countries the model produced PAB coverage estimates substantially inconsistent (too high or too low) and deviant from all other sources of information including coverage surveys, sero surveys and other programmatic evidences. One of the key limitations of the model was the failure to accommodate history of all TTCV doses by district where populations at risk have been reached by TT SIAs. The modelling method was later abandoned.
3) History of methods used and current approach used to monitor and report PAB

The methodology to estimate PAB did evolve over time with the progressive implementation of the WHO recommended 5 dose TTCV schedule and implementation of 3 rounds of TT SIAS in high risk districts of many countries.

-From 1986 to 1989: the administrative reporting of TT2+ was used. Most countries had the policy to administer 2 doses of TT in each pregnancy at the time, and TT SIAs in high risk districts were not yet implemented as a strategy to eliminate MNT. Results of nationwide TT coverage surveys were used over administrative reports as they did overcome the weakness of poor data quality - incomplete and over reporting.

-From 1990 to 2003.  The WHO recommended 5 doses policy was introduced in most countries and TT SIAs targeting WRA took place yearly in many low and lower middle income countries. EPI coverage evaluation survey (CES) and MICS/DHS methods for TT coverage assessment were amended to take into account all doses of TTCV administered during pregnancies and during SIAs. However, many DHS and MICS did not always follow through the WHO recommended survey protocol.

The routine PAB monitoring at DTP1 contact methodology was introduced in the late 1990s to improve the quality of TT protection data as better performing countries started reporting lower coverage using the TT2+ coverage monitoring method. However, only few countries applied it successfully nationwide.

During those years the method used by WHO and UNICEF to report national level TT2+ coverage estimates for each country was the result of the reported administrative TT2+ coverage data adjusted with the reported TT SIAs coverage achieved.

Each Protocol and results of nationwide EPI CES /MICS/DHS coverage survey results for tetanus protection were reviewed by WHO and UNICEF in consultation with country EPI managers. Where the surveys include the history of TT doses during past pregnancies and TT SIAs, the coverage results were used to report PAB estimate overriding administrative method mentioned above.
Where survey data was not available, the reported administrative PAB coverage in the few countries that implemented this method nationwide was used.

The review also took into account MNTE status and TT coverage survey results in the worst performing district(s) as surrogate information for the whole country to back up reported or surveyed estimates.
2003- 2017: UNICEF and WHO continue to use and review and compare the multiple data sources available as mentioned for the 1990 to 2003 period:
1) Administrative reporting of TT2+ dose (unfortunately this excludes the growing contribution of the private sector and post injury doses)
2) Most recent validated EPI CES/MICS/DHS results after review of the protocol /questionnaire (the survey usually include the private sector contribution)
3) TT SIAs coverage results, timing, duration of protection and proportion of the population covered by TT SIAs over time
4) Routine PAB monitoring at DTP1 contact method when reliable data is available, as obtained from Morocco and Tunisia
5) TT2+ coverage results in worst performing district(s) during MNTE LQA validation surveys

6) Surrogate EPI programme performance indicators such as DTP1 , DTP3, coverage and expert opinion. Reproductive health indicators like antenatal care (ANC) and skilled birth attendance (SBA) that are directly linked to tetanus protection are factored in MNTE validation assessments.
7) Previous 3 years reported estimates for EPI coverage to accommodate incomplete reporting of last previous year
Following the data review the final PAB estimate is a consensus between WHO and UNICEF technical staff and rational for each country data is incorporated.

The current reported PAB estimates based on TTCV protection are still very likely underestimating the true level of tetanus protection in some countries because historical doses of TTCV including childhood doses, 2nd year of life booster doses, school-based doses, MenA vaccine doses and post injury doses, and recently, in some countries, doses given for voluntary medical male circumcision (VMMC) etc. are not systematically documented and/or included in the estimates.
